{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S2 — Auth framework (composite audience choke point) + Resource-Server wiring + static verifier\n\n## Why\nThis story delivers the authentication admission core — the provider-agnostic seam every verifier\nplugs into, and the single audience/fail-closed choke point the whole security model rests on —\nplus the first (dependency-free) verifier so the path is exercisable locally: the static bearer\ntoken (the \"PAT\" half of the confirmed floor).\n\n## What\n- Extend the flat `McpConfig`/`_SECTIONS['mcp']` (from S1) with flat scalar auth keys:\n  `auth_enabled` (bool, default false), `auth_strategies` (comma-separated → ordered list),\n  `auth_issuer_url` (str), `auth_resource_server_url` (str — the SINGLE resource identifier),\n  `auth_required_scopes` (comma-separated → list), and `auth_static_tokens_file` (str path). Each is\n  one field + one flat coercer entry; register in `MCP_ENV_VARS`/`server.json` and regenerate\n  `docs/mcp-reference.md`/`docs/env-vars.md`. There is **one** `auth_resource_server_url` for the\n  whole server: it is what the RFC 9728 PRM advertises AND the audience every verifier is checked\n  against — never a separate per-verifier audience. Per-verifier params (S3–S6) are additional flat\n  keys those stories add; the flat schema holds **one instance per strategy type** (for multiple\n  issuers, use the custom verifier) — documented in S7.\n- New module `src/rebar/_mcp_auth.py`:\n  - A `CompositeTokenVerifier` that is the **single audience + fail-closed choke point**. It tries\n    each active verifier in order; a verifier returning an `AccessToken` is a candidate; a verifier\n    returning `None` means \"not my token\" → try next; a verifier that **raises** is logged and\n    treated as **non-acceptance** (never acceptance) → try next. For any candidate token the\n    composite then **rejects unless `token.resource` is present AND equals `auth_resource_server_url`**\n    (RFC 8707) — this re-check is independent of the sub-verifier, so no verifier (including a buggy\n    or malicious custom one that returns `resource=None`) can bypass audience validation. If no\n    verifier yields a valid, audience-matching token, the request is denied (401). An exception never\n    yields acceptance.\n  - A config→verifier **factory** built from `auth_strategies`, whose value vocabulary is the CLOSED\n    set `static | jwt | introspection | proxy | custom`. An unrecognized entry is a **hard startup\n    error**; `auth_enabled=true` producing an **empty** composite is a hard startup error; and\n    `auth_enabled` with `transport=http` where no verifier is wired **refuses to start** (never a\n    silent open endpoint).\n  - The **`StaticBearerVerifier`**: reads the secrets file (below), stores only SHA-256 digests,\n    compares with `hmac.compare_digest`, assigns each token's `client_id`/`scopes`, and stamps every\n    returned `AccessToken` with `resource=auth_resource_server_url` so it passes the composite check.\n- Wire it in `build_server`: when `auth_enabled`, pass `token_verifier=CompositeTokenVerifier(…)` and\n  `auth=AuthSettings(issuer_url=auth_issuer_url, resource_server_url=auth_resource_server_url,\n  required_scopes=auth_required_scopes)` to `FastMCP`, so the SDK serves the RFC 9728 PRM (a SINGLE\n  `authorization_servers` entry derived from `issuer_url`) and emits 401 + `WWW-Authenticate`.\n  Resolve S1's unauthenticated-HTTP guard against the real `auth_enabled`.\n- **No-log redaction:** add a redaction helper used on every auth error/log path (composite raise\n  handler, verifier errors) so no token/secret substring is ever emitted.\n\n**Static-token secrets format (parsed by the verifier, NOT the TOML coercer).** The per-token\nrecords live in the JSON/TOML file named by `auth_static_tokens_file`, parsed by the\n`StaticBearerVerifier` at load — outside the flat coercer (which cannot hold variable-length records).\nEach record supplies `client_id`, `scopes` (list), and the secret as EXACTLY ONE of: `token_env`\n(the NAME of an env var holding the plaintext — preferred; nothing secret in the file), or\n`token_sha256` (a precomputed lowercase SHA-256 hex digest, safe ONLY for a high-entropy token). The\nverifier resolves plaintext from `token_env` and stores only its SHA-256; a record embedding a\nplaintext literal, or missing both fields, is rejected at startup. Static tokens MUST be ≥128-bit\nrandom; provide a `rebar` helper/documented one-liner to generate one (S7 documents the entropy\nrequirement and that static tokens are non-expiring, so `token_env` is preferred).\n\n## Approach & rationale\nModel the framework on the SDK's own `TokenVerifier`/`AuthSettings` seam (the blessed extension\npoint the `simple-auth` example uses), and make the composite the ONE place audience + fail-closed\nare enforced, because the SDK's `BearerAuthBackend` never inspects `.resource` (grounded against\nmcp 1.28.1) — there is no backstop behind the verifier. Keep config flat to fit `coerce_sparse`. A\ncomposite (not a single selected strategy) lets a deployment accept static PAT for CI AND OIDC JWTs\nfor humans at once (the GitHub model). Static bearer first because it needs no external IdP, making\nthe end-to-end 401/200/403 path locally verifiable.\n\n## Scope\nThe auth framework (composite choke point + factory + flat config + PRM/401 wiring + redaction) and\nthe **static** verifier only. JWKS/JWT (S3), introspection (S4), trusted-proxy (S5), custom (S6)\nregister additional verifiers on this seam. Subset of the epic. Depends on S1.\n\n## Security\nBoundary-crossing. Enforced here: the composite audience re-check (every accepted token's\n`resource` == `auth_resource_server_url`); fail-closed (raise = non-acceptance, misconfig/unknown-\nstrategy/empty-composite/no-verifier-over-HTTP = refuse start, no verifier accepting = 401);\nconstant-time static compare; only SHA-256 digests held (no plaintext, no plaintext in config);\ntokens/secrets never logged (redaction + test); a positive `expires_at` is set where a token has one\n(never 0, which the SDK treats as no-expiry). Static tokens are dev/internal-grade, ≥128-bit, and\nnon-expiring (documented in S7).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The flat `auth_enabled`/`auth_strategies`/`auth_issuer_url`/`auth_resource_server_url`/\n      `auth_required_scopes`/`auth_static_tokens_file` keys exist as `McpConfig` fields + flat\n      coercer entries, appear in `MCP_ENV_VARS`/`server.json`, and the regenerated reference docs +\n      `scripts/check_server_manifest.py` pass (observable: manifest drift test green; a round-trip\n      test reads each key from TOML and from its env var).\n- [ ] Integration test (tier: integration — httpx `ASGITransport` against the SDK's Streamable-HTTP\n      ASGI entrypoint) asserts, with static auth enabled: unauthenticated → **401** + a\n      `WWW-Authenticate` header carrying the RFC 9728 `resource_metadata` URL (observable oracle:\n      status + header value).\n- [ ] Integration test asserts the PRM is served at `/.well-known/oauth-protected-resource/…` with a\n      single `authorization_servers` entry (observable oracle: HTTP 200 + JSON field).\n- [ ] Integration test asserts: valid static token → **200**; unknown/invalid token → 401; a\n      principal lacking a `required_scope` → **403**; and a token whose `resource` ≠\n      `auth_resource_server_url` (injected via a stub verifier in the composite) → 401 at the\n      composite regardless of the sub-verifier (negative controls included).\n- [ ] Integration test asserts session-id replay cannot hijack a principal: an `Mcp-Session-Id`\n      obtained by one authenticated client, replayed by a DIFFERENT client that presents no valid\n      token of its own, is NEVER served in the first principal's authenticated context (single\n      observable oracle: the replayed request does not return the original principal's authorized\n      access — it is denied 401 / treated as unauthenticated).\n- [ ] Unit test asserts the composite contract: `None` → try next; an `AccessToken` with matching\n      `resource` → accept; a verifier that **raises** → logged, non-acceptance, request denied (no\n      swallow-to-accept), with a control where a raising verifier ordered after an accepting one is\n      never consulted.\n- [ ] Unit test asserts fail-closed startup: an unknown `auth_strategies` entry, an empty composite\n      with `auth_enabled=true`, and `auth_enabled` + `transport=http` with no verifier wired each\n      refuse to start (observable oracle: startup raises a clear message).\n- [ ] Unit test asserts `StaticBearerVerifier` holds only SHA-256 digests (not plaintext), uses a\n      constant-time compare, stamps `resource=auth_resource_server_url`, and rejects a secrets-file\n      record with a plaintext literal or missing both `token_env`/`token_sha256`.\n- [ ] Unit test asserts no token/secret substring appears in emitted logs across the composite\n      raise-handler and a verifier error path (observable oracle: captured logs contain neither the\n      token nor the secret).\n- [ ] With `auth_enabled=false`, an integration test (with `allow_unauthenticated_http=true`) asserts\n      no auth middleware: a no-token HTTP request gets a normal MCP response (not 401), and the stdio\n      suite `tests/interfaces/facades/test_mcp.py` still passes unchanged.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass.\n\n## Compatibility\nAdditive; auth off by default. Only ADDS flat scalar keys to the existing flat `McpConfig`/\n`_SECTIONS['mcp']` — no change to the coercer architecture, stdio, or the existing tools. Depends on\nS1's transport + SDK pin."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784071918424330001,"uuid":"8c8fcd6a-cd19-494d-b4e1-d48502a4f539"}